I'm... oh.

254
00:09:48,622 --> 00:09:50,123
My dad was your wingman?

255
00:09:50,190 --> 00:09:53,126
This is really
messing with my head.

256
00:09:53,193 --> 00:09:55,095
Barney, is my dad cool?

257
00:09:55,162 --> 00:09:56,730
I'm not done.

258
00:09:56,797 --> 00:09:59,466
So, your dad stays
to finish his drink,
but I take off

259
00:09:59,532 --> 00:10:02,469
because I have to be up early
for Mass with your mom.

260
00:10:02,535 --> 00:10:04,171
Sure.

261
00:10:04,237 --> 00:10:06,640
Anyway, I realize that I left
my phone on the bar,

262
00:10:06,707 --> 00:10:08,041
so I come back...

263
00:10:12,045 --> 00:10:13,613
(whispers):
Oh, my God...

264
00:10:13,681 --> 00:10:15,949
Mmm...

265
00:10:17,751 --> 00:10:19,687
Oh, my God.

266
00:10:19,753 --> 00:10:22,422
Is that really...

267
00:10:22,489 --> 00:10:24,357
Oh, my God!

268
00:10:24,424 --> 00:10:25,826
I know.

269
00:10:25,893 --> 00:10:28,962
Can you believe your dad
rack-jacked me like that?

270
00:10:35,568 --> 00:10:37,905
My dad made out with
Wendy the waitress?

271
00:10:37,971 --> 00:10:39,306
He cheated on my mom?

272
00:10:39,372 --> 00:10:40,507
No, that's impossible.

273
00:10:40,573 --> 00:10:43,911
Ted, it's a well-known statistic
that 83% of people

274
00:10:43,977 --> 00:10:46,814
married longer than six months
are seeing someone on the side.

275
00:10:46,880 --> 00:10:48,548
Do you know that
when you make up

276
00:10:48,615 --> 00:10:49,750
a statistic,
you always use "83%"?

277
00:10:49,817 --> 00:10:51,719
You think I'm lying.

278
00:10:51,785 --> 00:10:54,221
Well, have you done
any surveys on the subject?

279
00:10:54,287 --> 00:10:55,555
Because the good people at

280
00:10:55,622 --> 00:10:59,760
www.swingers.open-marriage-is
natural\legalize-polygamy.org

281
00:10:59,827 --> 00:11:01,695
have, and they beg to differ.

282
00:11:01,762 --> 00:11:03,196
That's not a real Web site.

283
00:11:03,263 --> 00:11:05,432
Oh, and I suppose
I didn't get a real T-shirt

284
00:11:05,498 --> 00:11:06,566
for running in their 10K.

285
00:11:06,633 --> 00:11:08,101
(knock at door)

286
00:11:11,271 --> 00:11:12,205
Hi, Dad.
Hey, Ted.

287
00:11:12,272 --> 00:11:13,206
Barney.

288
00:11:13,273 --> 00:11:14,474
TED:
Enjoying your
vacation so far?

289
00:11:14,541 --> 00:11:16,076
Oh, yeah.

290
00:11:16,143 --> 00:11:18,211
Uh, listen, can I speak
to you outside for a sec?

291
00:11:18,278 --> 00:11:19,279
Sure.

292
00:11:23,283 --> 00:11:25,318
So you went out
with Barney last night?

293
00:11:25,385 --> 00:11:26,586
Yeah.

294
00:11:26,653 --> 00:11:27,888
You have a good time?

295
00:11:27,955 --> 00:11:29,857
Oh, yeah, yeah. Sorry
you couldn't join us.

296
00:11:32,192 --> 00:11:34,661
Yeah.

297
00:11:34,728 --> 00:11:36,396
So...

298
00:11:36,463 --> 00:11:38,131
What?

299
00:11:38,198 --> 00:11:40,734
Well...

300
00:11:40,801 --> 00:11:42,702
Well what?

301
00:11:44,437 --> 00:11:47,407
You think Cerrano's got
a shot at the RBI title?

302
00:11:49,309 --> 00:11:51,011
I wanted to confront him,
but I couldn't.

303
00:11:51,078 --> 00:11:52,746
I guess I got
the let's-not-talk-about-

304
00:11:52,813 --> 00:11:54,114
anything-
uncomfortable gene.

305
00:11:54,181 --> 00:11:55,916
Well, you didn't get your
dad's close-the-deal gene,

306
00:11:55,983 --> 00:11:57,017
that's for sure.

307
00:11:57,084 --> 00:11:58,485
Smile.

308
00:11:58,551 --> 00:11:59,820
Great.

309
00:11:59,887 --> 00:12:01,855
I don't care how
unpleasant it is.

310
00:12:01,922 --> 00:12:03,256
You have to
talk to him.

311
00:12:03,323 --> 00:12:04,191
Not now.

312
00:12:04,257 --> 00:12:05,692
Okay, if you
don't, I will.

313
00:12:05,759 --> 00:12:06,927
Robin...!

314
00:12:06,994 --> 00:12:09,529
TED:
Okay, now I got to back up

315
00:12:09,596 --> 00:12:10,898
all the way
to the beginning

316
00:12:10,964 --> 00:12:13,333
to tell you the me
and Robin part of the story.

317
00:12:15,335 --> 00:12:17,570
We were expecting my parents
at any minute.

318
00:12:17,637 --> 00:12:19,072
One last thing about my mom.

319
00:12:19,139 --> 00:12:20,673
She grills every
single one of

320
00:12:20,740 --> 00:12:23,010
my girlfriends about when we're
gonna get married and have kids.

321
00:12:23,076 --> 00:12:24,945
But this is the first time
she's meeting me.

322
00:12:25,012 --> 00:12:25,913
Doesn't matter.

323
00:12:25,979 --> 00:12:27,380
And you'll know it's coming

324
00:12:27,447 --> 00:12:30,183
when she mentions my cousin
Stacy-- six kids in five years.

325
00:12:30,250 --> 00:12:32,119
The woman's basically
a ride at a water park.

326
00:12:32,185 --> 00:12:35,989
But I don't want
to get married and have kids.

327
00:12:36,056 --> 00:12:37,590
What am I supposed to say?

328
00:12:37,657 --> 00:12:39,326
You know what?

329
00:12:39,392 --> 00:12:41,494
You're an adult with
perfectly valid opinions.

330
00:12:41,561 --> 00:12:43,463
You shouldn't have to
apologize for them.

331
00:12:43,530 --> 00:12:45,765
I'm gonna lie.
I would.

332
00:12:45,833 --> 00:12:47,767
Thanks again for
letting me have

333
00:12:47,835 --> 00:12:49,202
the U2 box set.

334
00:12:49,269 --> 00:12:51,504
I know how important
it is to you.

335
00:12:52,772 --> 00:12:54,107
I talked to Aunt
Caroline the other day.

336
00:12:54,174 --> 00:12:56,443
Stacy's pregnant again.

337
00:12:56,509 --> 00:12:59,312
Oh, good for her.

338
00:12:59,379 --> 00:13:00,547
So, dear...

339
00:13:00,613 --> 00:13:02,916
Oh, boy.
Tell us what it's like
being a journalist.

340
00:13:02,983 --> 00:13:04,284
I'm just not ready.

341
00:13:04,351 --> 00:13:06,453
Okay. No pressure.

342
00:13:06,519 --> 00:13:07,988
Oh.

343
00:13:08,055 --> 00:13:10,523
Uh, I thought you, um...

344
00:13:10,590 --> 00:13:11,624
It's great.

345
00:13:11,691 --> 00:13:12,792
Good.

346
00:13:12,860 --> 00:13:13,961
Focus on your job now,

347
00:13:14,027 --> 00:13:16,129
because your career clock
is ticking.

348
00:13:16,196 --> 00:13:17,865
There's time
for marriage and kids

349
00:13:17,931 --> 00:13:19,867
and all that other stuff later.

350
00:13:21,568 --> 00:13:23,003
Ooh, a piano!

351
00:13:24,671 --> 00:13:26,006
TED:
You lucked out with

352
00:13:26,073 --> 00:13:27,374
my mom last
night, huh?

353
00:13:27,440 --> 00:13:28,842
What a relief, right?

354
00:13:28,909 --> 00:13:30,577
Oh, absolutely.
Whew, what a relief it is

355
00:13:30,643 --> 00:13:31,845
to know I'm the one girlfriend

356
00:13:31,912 --> 00:13:33,613
your mom doesn't want you
to have kids with.

357
00:13:33,680 --> 00:13:36,483
Hooray?

358
00:13:36,549 --> 00:13:39,019
I mean, did she really think
that your college girlfriend

359
00:13:39,086 --> 00:13:41,221
Cheryl would pop out
attractive children?

360
00:13:41,288 --> 00:13:43,256
'Cause I've seen pictures,
and, I'm sorry,

361
00:13:43,323 --> 00:13:45,425
that girl had a brow ridge
like a caveman.

362
00:13:45,492 --> 00:13:48,495
Come on, she was just
frowning under direct light.

363
00:13:48,561 --> 00:13:50,730
And besides, that's not even
what I liked about her.

364
00:13:50,797 --> 00:13:52,900
It was her...
It's not important.

365
00:13:55,435 --> 00:13:57,137
What happened to
Marshall and Lily?

366
00:13:57,204 --> 00:13:58,405
They've been fighting lately.

367
00:13:58,471 --> 00:14:00,540
They're probably off
somewhere going at it.

368
00:14:00,607 --> 00:14:02,009
More coffee?

369
00:14:02,075 --> 00:14:04,912
Oh, no, thank you.

370
00:14:04,978 --> 00:14:06,813
Isn't she sweet?

371
00:14:06,880 --> 00:14:09,716
Well, if she's so sweet, maybe
she should have Ted's babies.

372
00:14:09,782 --> 00:14:12,319
Excuse me?

373
00:14:12,385 --> 00:14:14,321
Nothing.

374
00:14:19,759 --> 00:14:20,894
LILY:
Just a minute.

375
00:14:20,961 --> 00:14:22,362
MARSHALL:
Maybe less.

376
00:14:22,429 --> 00:14:23,997
Robin, dear.

377
00:14:24,064 --> 00:14:25,966
Did I say something
to upset you?

378
00:14:26,033 --> 00:14:27,767
Why don't you want me
to have your grandkids?

379
00:14:27,834 --> 00:14:30,670
Do you want to have
my grandkids?

380
00:14:30,737 --> 00:14:31,905
No!

381
00:14:31,972 --> 00:14:33,606
I mean, I don't know.

382
00:14:33,673 --> 00:14:34,607
I just...

383
00:14:34,674 --> 00:14:35,909
I want you to want me

384
00:14:35,976 --> 00:14:37,044
to want to have your grandkids.

385
00:14:37,110 --> 00:14:38,111
And you should.

386
00:14:38,178 --> 00:14:39,579
I'm a genetic gold mine.

387
00:14:40,347 --> 00:14:41,548
No family history of diabetes

388
00:14:41,614 --> 00:14:42,682
or heart disease.

389
00:14:42,749 --> 00:14:45,585
Everyone has nonporous teeth
and perfect eyesight.

390
00:14:46,819 --> 00:14:48,021
I had one schizophrenic uncle,

391
00:14:48,088 --> 00:14:50,257
but even he had perfect vision.

392
00:14:50,323 --> 00:14:52,259
Which was unfortunate
for the people around

393
00:14:52,325 --> 00:14:55,028
the bell tower he was in,
but still he was

394
00:14:55,095 --> 00:14:56,629
a very fine man, and...

395
00:14:56,696 --> 00:14:57,897
Excuse me. Sorry.

396
00:14:57,965 --> 00:14:59,466
Didn't know that
there was a line.

397
00:14:59,532 --> 00:15:01,568
Marshall, your zipper.

398
00:15:01,634 --> 00:15:02,635
Oh.

399
00:15:09,442 --> 00:15:12,679
Robin, it's not that I
don't want grandkids.

400
00:15:12,745 --> 00:15:15,148
It's just I don't think
anyone should make the mistake

401
00:15:15,215 --> 00:15:17,017
of getting married too young.

402
00:15:17,084 --> 00:15:18,185
Why do you say that?

403
00:15:18,251 --> 00:15:19,786
I mean, you got married
pretty young.

404
00:15:19,852 --> 00:15:21,021
That wasn't a mistake.

405
00:15:22,322 --> 00:15:23,890
Was it?

406
00:15:23,957 --> 00:15:26,026
(whispers):
Well...

407
00:15:26,093 --> 00:15:27,760
Okay, there's something
you don't know.

408
00:15:27,827 --> 00:15:29,829
WAITRESS:
Smile.

409
00:15:29,896 --> 00:15:31,464
I wish your face
would melt off.

410
00:15:31,531 --> 00:15:32,932
I wish your eyeballs
would explode.

411
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:34,001
I'm gonna kill him.

412
00:15:34,067 --> 00:15:35,068
I don't care how
unpleasant it is,

413
00:15:35,135 --> 00:15:36,303
you have to
talk to him.

414
00:15:36,369 --> 00:15:37,971
Not now.
Okay, if you
don't, I will.

415
00:15:38,038 --> 00:15:40,207
Robin...!

416
00:15:40,273 --> 00:15:42,742
Oh, gosh, let me help you
pick those up, sweetheart.

417
00:15:42,809 --> 00:15:44,411
Sweetheart?

418
00:15:44,477 --> 00:15:45,812
Sweetheart?!

419
00:15:45,878 --> 00:15:47,047
The only sweetheart in your life

420
00:15:47,114 --> 00:15:48,281
should be the woman you
married 30 years ago,

421
00:15:48,348 --> 00:15:49,983
not the waitress
at the bar last night

422
00:15:50,050 --> 00:15:51,284
and not this clumsy floozy!

423
00:15:51,351 --> 00:15:53,453
I'm sorry, you're
not a floozy.

424
00:15:53,520 --> 00:15:55,188
I'm upset, I don't know
what I'm saying.

425
00:15:56,123 --> 00:15:57,590
But stay away from my dad.

426
00:15:59,092 --> 00:16:00,693
Ted, what are you talking about?

427
00:16:00,760 --> 00:16:02,095
Dad?

428
00:16:02,162 --> 00:16:04,964
You, uh, want
to tell Mom

429
00:16:05,032 --> 00:16:06,666
what happened at the bar
last night?

430
00:16:09,002 --> 00:16:11,071
Okay.

431
00:16:11,138 --> 00:16:13,140
I hooked up with a waitress.

432
00:16:13,906 --> 00:16:15,375
Oh.

433
00:16:15,442 --> 00:16:16,943
Oh?

434
00:16:17,010 --> 00:16:18,745
I mean, oh!

435
00:16:19,779 --> 00:16:21,981
Oh! Ooh!

436
00:16:22,049 --> 00:16:23,350
We're going to have
a serious talk

437
00:16:23,416 --> 00:16:24,951
about this when
we get home, Al.

438
00:16:25,018 --> 00:16:26,486
Oh, ooh!

439
00:16:26,553 --> 00:16:28,421
Serious talk?

440
00:16:28,488 --> 00:16:29,289
Mom, what...?

441
00:16:29,356 --> 00:16:30,757
He was kissing another woman.

442
00:16:30,823 --> 00:16:31,691
Don't you care?

443
00:16:31,758 --> 00:16:33,226
Mrs. Mosby?

444
00:16:36,229 --> 00:16:38,931
Ted, we weren't quite sure
how to tell you this...

445
00:16:38,998 --> 00:16:41,468
Your mother and I
are divorced.

446
00:16:45,305 --> 00:16:47,006
You...

447
00:16:47,074 --> 00:16:48,041
What do you mean
you're divorced?

448
00:16:48,108 --> 00:16:49,309
Since when?

449
00:16:49,376 --> 00:16:52,045
Oh, gosh, it's been
about nine months now.

450
00:16:52,112 --> 00:16:53,613
Closer to ten, I think.

451
00:16:53,680 --> 00:16:55,382
Time flies.
(chuckles)

452
00:16:55,448 --> 00:16:58,118
So ten months ago,
you just up and decided

453
00:16:58,185 --> 00:16:59,819
to get divorced
without telling me?

454
00:16:59,886 --> 00:17:01,488
No, it wasn't a
snap decision.

455
00:17:01,554 --> 00:17:03,690
We'd been separated
almost two years.

456
00:17:03,756 --> 00:17:05,625
How could you not tell me this?!

457
00:17:05,692 --> 00:17:09,062
We meant to, it just never
seemed like the right time.

458
00:17:09,129 --> 00:17:11,331
So last Christmas...?

459
00:17:11,398 --> 00:17:13,366
We talked about
telling you kids then,

460
00:17:13,433 --> 00:17:15,335
but it didn't seem
very Christmasy.

461
00:17:15,402 --> 00:17:18,205
I got you a tandem bike.

462
00:17:18,271 --> 00:17:19,406
Oh, it didn't
go to waste.

463
00:17:19,472 --> 00:17:21,108
Your mother and Frank
ride it all the time.

464
00:17:21,174 --> 00:17:22,875
Who the hell is Frank?!

465
00:17:22,942 --> 00:17:24,744
(chuckling):
Oh, great guy.

466
00:17:24,811 --> 00:17:26,379
I actually set them up.

467
00:17:26,446 --> 00:17:27,847
You remember Dr. Muchnik.

468
00:17:27,914 --> 00:17:29,316
He did your braces.

469
00:17:33,019 --> 00:17:34,487
Okay, my head's
about to explode,

470
00:17:34,554 --> 00:17:36,889
and I don't want to get it
all over everyone's waffles,

471
00:17:36,956 --> 00:17:38,525
so I am leaving.

472
00:17:38,591 --> 00:17:40,260
Teddy bear, oh...

473
00:17:44,197 --> 00:17:47,134
You know, he mentioned
he was divorced last night.

474
00:17:47,200 --> 00:17:48,501
I totally spaced on that.

475
00:17:50,937 --> 00:17:52,539
Ooh, no line
at the omelet station.

476
00:17:59,146 --> 00:18:00,447
Lily...

477
00:18:00,513 --> 00:18:03,516
I'm sorry that I said
all those things.

478
00:18:03,583 --> 00:18:05,352
Me, too.

479
00:18:07,420 --> 00:18:10,056
I just find it really confusing
to be around you right now.

480
00:18:10,123 --> 00:18:11,291
It's the same for me.

481
00:18:12,692 --> 00:18:14,527
I think we're probably
both better off

482
00:18:14,594 --> 00:18:16,963
trying to keep some
distance for a while.

483
00:18:17,029 --> 00:18:19,266
Yeah, I think you're right.

484
00:18:27,507 --> 00:18:28,841
Are you wearing
a push-up bra?

485
00:18:28,908 --> 00:18:30,243
Did you Mystic
Tan your calves?

486
00:18:30,310 --> 00:18:33,079
I withdraw the question.

487
00:18:33,146 --> 00:18:36,949
We're sorry we didn't say
anything about the divorce.

488
00:18:37,016 --> 00:18:38,618
It was wrong
not to tell you.

489
00:18:38,685 --> 00:18:40,620
Thank you.

490
00:18:40,687 --> 00:18:42,054
But listen,
don't tell your sister.

491
00:18:42,121 --> 00:18:43,323
It would just
upset her.

492
00:18:43,390 --> 00:18:46,326
No, this is
ridiculous!

493
00:18:46,393 --> 00:18:49,162
We have to start talking about
stuff, and not just baseball.

494
00:18:49,229 --> 00:18:51,598
Indians won today
on a walk-off double.

495
00:18:51,664 --> 00:18:54,100
Against the Red Sox?
Boy, that's a big win.

496
00:18:54,167 --> 00:18:55,268
No. No. No.

497
00:18:55,335 --> 00:18:56,869
We're not gonna
blow past this.

498
00:18:56,936 --> 00:18:57,870
I mean, I don't even

499
00:18:57,937 --> 00:18:59,206
know who you people.

500
00:18:59,272 --> 00:19:00,673
I don't even know
how you met.

501
00:19:00,740 --> 00:19:02,842
I never told you
how I met your mother?

502
00:19:02,909 --> 00:19:03,710
No.

503
00:19:03,776 --> 00:19:04,944
Oh, great story.

504
00:19:05,011 --> 00:19:06,679
At a bar.

505
00:19:07,747 --> 00:19:09,816
That's it?

506
00:19:09,882 --> 00:19:12,185
That's what passes for
communication in our family?

507
00:19:12,252 --> 00:19:13,286
Man, when I have kids,

508
00:19:13,353 --> 00:19:15,388
and I tell them how
I met their mother,

509
00:19:15,455 --> 00:19:17,857
I'm gonna tell them everything,
the whole damn story.

510
00:19:19,826 --> 00:19:22,329
I think it was an Irish bar.

511
00:19:23,430 --> 00:19:25,832
I just, I don't...
I don't understand.

512
00:19:25,898 --> 00:19:26,999
You seemed so happy.

513
00:19:27,066 --> 00:19:28,167
When I was growing up,

514
00:19:28,235 --> 00:19:29,869
you seemed so...

515
00:19:29,936 --> 00:19:31,338
What happened?

516
00:19:31,404 --> 00:19:33,906
We just realized we're
very different people.

517
00:19:33,973 --> 00:19:36,309
Your father's kind of a
head-in-the-clouds romantic,

518
00:19:36,376 --> 00:19:38,110
and I'm much more
down to earth.

519
00:19:38,177 --> 00:19:39,979
So?

520
00:19:40,046 --> 00:19:41,248
Robin and I
are like that.

521
00:19:41,314 --> 00:19:42,315
That doesn't
mean anything.

522
00:19:42,382 --> 00:19:44,183
I wanted kids.

523
00:19:44,251 --> 00:19:46,286
And your mother...

524
00:19:46,353 --> 00:19:48,388
also wanted kids.

525
00:19:48,455 --> 00:19:51,491
Robin and I have
different views on families.

526
00:19:51,558 --> 00:19:53,460
We're not about to break up
because of it.

527
00:19:53,526 --> 00:19:55,962
On some level,
I always knew.

528
00:19:56,028 --> 00:19:58,431
I didn't even want to go out
with him in the beginning.

529
00:19:58,498 --> 00:20:01,734
But he spent months badgering
me until I finally gave in.

530
00:20:03,736 --> 00:20:05,238
Huh.

531
00:20:05,305 --> 00:20:07,440
Well, when you don't connect
on that many fundamental levels,

532
00:20:07,507 --> 00:20:09,276
it's only a matter of time
before you realize

533
00:20:09,342 --> 00:20:10,543
you're not meant
to be together.

534
00:20:12,312 --> 00:20:14,514
But we love Robin.

535
00:20:14,581 --> 00:20:15,848
MR. MOSBY:
Absolutely.

536
00:20:15,915 --> 00:20:18,084
Meeting you was
the highlight of my trip.

537
00:20:18,150 --> 00:20:20,720
Well, second highlight.

538
00:20:20,787 --> 00:20:22,489
MRS. MOSBY:
We'll see you inside.

539
00:20:22,555 --> 00:20:24,491
Sorry.

540
00:20:28,928 --> 00:20:30,196
Wow.

541
00:20:30,263 --> 00:20:31,931
I know.

542
00:20:31,998 --> 00:20:34,767
They love me!

543
00:20:34,834 --> 00:20:36,703
(chuckles)

544
00:20:39,439 --> 00:20:42,375
We are definitely going to
try and communicate more.

545
00:20:42,442 --> 00:20:43,843
From now on,
full disclosure.

546
00:20:43,910 --> 00:20:47,046
Good. Good, I think it'll be
really good for the family.

547
00:20:47,113 --> 00:20:48,281
By the way,
how's Grandma?

548
00:20:48,348 --> 00:20:50,450
She hasn't returned
my last couple calls.

549
00:20:57,290 --> 00:20:59,492
I'm gonna get
some juice.

550
00:21:01,828 --> 00:21:03,596
No.

551
00:21:04,697 --> 00:21:07,300
No.

552
00:21:07,367 --> 00:21:08,935
(chuckles)

553
00:21:09,001 --> 00:21:11,604
You missed a great game
last night. Real squeaker.

